<paragraph blockId="10.[160,1156,337,605]" box="[160,276,337,362]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1456">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,276,337,362]" inLineHeading="true" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1456" reason="3">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[160,1156,337,605]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1456">
Members of this genus are generally distinguishable from other hersiliid genera in the Palaearctic (except 
<emphasis box="[381,762,407,431]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1456">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Marusik &amp; Fet" authorityYear="2009" box="[381,537,407,431]" class="Arachnida" family="Hersiliidae" genus="Ovtsharenkoia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="10" pageNumber="1456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Ovtsharenkoia</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Marusik &amp; Fet" authorityYear="2009" box="[552,663,407,431]" class="Arachnida" family="Hersiliidae" genus="Deltshevia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="10" pageNumber="1456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Deltshevia</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Marusik &amp; Fet" authorityYear="2009" box="[678,762,407,431]" class="Arachnida" family="Hersiliidae" genus="Duninia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="10" pageNumber="1456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Duninia</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Mirshamsi &amp; Zamani &amp; Marusik, 2016" authorityName="Mirshamsi &amp; Zamani &amp; Marusik" authorityYear="2016" box="[827,929,407,431]" class="Arachnida" family="Hersiliidae" genus="Bastanius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="10" pageNumber="1456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[827,929,407,431]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1456">Bastanius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[941,1049,407,431]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1456" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
) by their short spinnerets (shorter than carapace). Furthermore, males can be diagnosed by their discoid tegulum, long and coiled embolus, and small tegular apophysis which is perpendicular to the axis of the palp (
<bibRefCitation author="Marusik YM &amp; Fet V" box="[502,786,511,535]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1456" pagination="75 - 114" refId="ref4820" refString="Marusik YM, Fet V. 2009. A survey of East Palearctic Hersiliola Thorell, 1870 (Araneae: Hersiliidae), with description of three new genera. Zookeys. 16: 75 - 114." type="journal article" year="2009">Marusik and Fet 2009: 89</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 4.1−4.4). The females can be diagnosed by their insemination ducts, which are coiled around the fertilisation ducts and uncoiled around the upper loop (
<bibRefCitation author="Marusik YM &amp; Fet V" box="[531,813,581,605]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1456" pagination="75 - 114" refId="ref4820" refString="Marusik YM, Fet V. 2009. A survey of East Palearctic Hersiliola Thorell, 1870 (Araneae: Hersiliidae), with description of three new genera. Zookeys. 16: 75 - 114." type="journal article" year="2009">Marusik and Fet 2009: 92</bibRefCitation>
, figs 7.1, 7.5, 7.6, 7.12, 8.1 
<emphasis box="[1097,1110,581,605]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1456">–</emphasis>
8.4).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
